						               													<description>The game takes place in Southern seas of a fairyland. You make a decision to try your luck, fit out a schooner and set your sail towards the South. After long and painful days of sailing towers of a large port town appear in the horizon...&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In the game, each participant assumes the role of the owner of the ship, on which he sails around the bay, depicted on the colorful playing field.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players have quite a lot of different opportunities: buy / sell goods in cities, improve their ships, buy guns, seize cities, invest their money in bills of exchange, build forts, and of course, fight each other.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The rules of the game are very simple (but not primitive) and are intended, rather, for children. In addition, the game does not have a goal as such: we simply sail across the bay, enriching ourselves by trading and looting each other, trying to surpass the wealth of our opponents.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players usually set their own rules for the game, ether to accumulate a set amount of wealth or fight other players until they don't have money to buy new supplies.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;However, this is one of the few Russian-made board games in the 1990s, which will be really interesting for the participants to play: calculate where to swim, how to avoid or impose a battle, and how to protect your savings with promissory notes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The spirit of sea adventure calls you.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
